This step (`applyOverrides`) returns a boolean flag named `skipAnalysis` indicating whether analysis will be executed or not. Initially, all operation config params are null, after applying overriden, there will be 2 cases:

- If there is **no (valid) overrides** or operation config **not fully overrides** (i.e. all params are not null). The analysis will be conducted for that operation (`skipAnalysis=false`)
- If **all params of the operation config are overridden**, the analysis will be skipped (`skipAnalysis=true`)

**Example:** we have user override for op `conv2d_1` defined as below

```
conv2dConfigOverrides = {
 "conv2d_1": {
 "weightsDtype": "bf16",
 "activation": "relu"
 // everything else is NOT specified
 }
}
```

After applying override, the `Conv2dConfigOverrideParams` for op `conv2d_1` is as below:

```
Conv2dConfigOverrideParams params;

// These are overriden
params.weightsDtype = ttcore::DataType::BFloat16;
params.activation = UnaryOpType::ReLU;

// All other fields remain nullopt
params.activationParams = nullopt;
params.deallocateActivation = nullopt;
params.reallocateHaloOutput = nullopt;
params.actBlockHOverride = nullopt;
// ...
```

Because the config not fully defined, it will go through next step to determine other missing params.

First validates if the operation is a valid analysis target (has results, has ranked tensor type, not an EmptyOp)

```
bool LegalOpLayoutAnalysis::isValidAnalysisTarget(Operation *op) {
 if (op->getNumResults() == 0) {
 return false;
 }
 if (!llvm::isa<mlir::RankedTensorType>(op->getResult(0).getType())) {
 return false;
 }
 if (llvm::isa<mlir::tt::ttnn::EmptyOp>(op)) {
 return false;
 }
 return true;
}
```

The main algorithm is implemented in `fillTTNNLayoutAttrs()`, which:

- Get output tensor type (`RankedTensorType`) from operation → get layout from `tensorType`.

```
// Get output tensor type.
RankedTensorType tensorType =
 mlir::cast<RankedTensorType>(op->getResult(0).getType());
TTNNLayoutAttr layout = mlir::cast<TTNNLayoutAttr>(tensorType.getEncoding());
fillTTNNLayoutAttrs(layout);
```

- Retrieves layouts from the tensor-level analysis categorized by scalar type, and separates layouts into interleaved and sharded categories

```
// Sharded layouts for row major and tile are kept separate so we can combine
// them equally, and avoid having only RM or Tile layouts
std::vector<TTNNLayoutAttr> shardedLayoutsRowMajor;
std::vector<TTNNLayoutAttr> shardedLayoutsTile;
std::vector<TTNNLayoutAttr> interleavedLayouts;
```

- Sort the layouts by grid volume for each `shardedLayous` by grid volume, so can take the largest one first.
- Selects top layouts respecting the `maxShardedConfigs` limit

